but because every design decision focused around that.

245
00:10:33,461 --> 00:10:37,628
it came through and people actually regurgitated that back to me and that was kind of amazing.

246
00:10:39,395 --> 00:10:42,317
I don't know, as a designer and as a creative,

247
00:10:42,317 --> 00:10:44,498
it's not often that I can do something.

248
00:10:44,498 --> 00:10:47,160
Usually it's like, oh, did you feel anxiety

249
00:10:47,160 --> 00:10:47,700
when you were playing it?

250
00:10:47,700 --> 00:10:50,682
And they're like, yeah, I think I did.

251
00:10:50,682 --> 00:10:52,063
That's usually what it is,

252
00:10:52,063 --> 00:10:54,305
but I was getting people coming to me,

253
00:10:54,305 --> 00:10:55,325
saying my artistic intent,

254
00:10:55,325 --> 00:10:56,966
and that was blowing my mind away.

255
00:10:56,966 --> 00:10:57,707
And I think that's why,

256
00:10:57,707 --> 00:11:01,910
is because everything revolved around those things.

257
00:11:01,910 --> 00:11:03,951
Let me give you guys a quick example

258
00:11:03,951 --> 00:11:05,932
of a game that was very inspiring to me.

259
00:11:05,932 --> 00:11:08,274
Adam Saltzman and Robin Arnaud made this game called Capsule.

260
00:11:08,935 --> 00:11:11,321
And if this will play. This game blew my mind when I saw it.

261
00:11:18,207 --> 00:11:20,948
Everything in this game is working together.

262
00:11:20,948 --> 00:11:23,669
There is a bend of the CRT monitor,

263
00:11:23,669 --> 00:11:26,330
there are boops and beeps,

264
00:11:26,330 --> 00:11:30,211
there is a scan line that goes down.

265
00:11:30,211 --> 00:11:31,151
The UI, the sound design,

266
00:11:31,151 --> 00:11:33,292
everything about this game screamed to me

267
00:11:33,292 --> 00:11:37,313
that I was in this claustrophobic little bubble in space

268
00:11:37,313 --> 00:11:39,754
and I had this crappy little CRT monitor

269
00:11:39,754 --> 00:11:41,954
and my instruments and that's all I had.

270
00:11:41,954 --> 00:11:44,375
And this blew my mind and I was like,

271
00:11:44,375 --> 00:11:46,256
if they can do this, then I can do this.

272
00:11:47,576 --> 00:11:49,257
you know, and that's when you steal ideas.

273
00:11:49,257 --> 00:11:52,559
So, and actually you don't only have to steal ideas

274
00:11:52,559 --> 00:11:54,521
because at the end of the development of Duskers,

275
00:11:54,521 --> 00:11:56,922
I got Robin to come over and help do sound design.

276
00:11:56,922 --> 00:11:57,743
So you can steal people too.

277
00:11:57,743 --> 00:12:00,124
So there's like a whole stealing,

278
00:12:00,124 --> 00:12:02,926
it's like it's endless what you can steal.

279
00:12:02,926 --> 00:12:06,028
So I just kind of wanted to use that as a quick example.

280
00:12:06,028 --> 00:12:07,509
So now let's get into the fun stuff.

281
00:12:07,509 --> 00:12:09,771
Let's talk about Duskers and how all of this stuff.

282
00:12:10,371 --> 00:12:15,333
affected Duskers. So let's just at the beginning of Duskers I had this idea. It

283
00:12:15,333 --> 00:12:18,834
was like you were Han and Chewie and you owed some gangsters money and there was

284
00:12:18,834 --> 00:12:22,775
this Bermuda Triangle of destroyed spaceships and you were gonna go in and

285
00:12:22,775 --> 00:12:27,077
basically tomb raid them and there were gonna be tower defense mechanics because

286
00:12:27,077 --> 00:12:31,139
you were gonna make sure that as you opened up doors the bad things didn't

287
00:12:31,139 --> 00:12:34,920
come out and eat you and so your little drones would you know fire on them and

288
00:12:34,920 --> 00:12:38,061
all and you know so this was originally like kind of the concept and that's the

289
00:12:38,061 --> 00:12:39,462
thing this this talk isn't really about

290
00:12:39,842 --> 00:12:44,348
Ideation this is kind of like once you're kind of going like how do you find your way?

291
00:12:44,348 --> 00:12:45,690
and so

292
00:12:45,690 --> 00:12:48,794
Not much of this made it into duskers actually

293
00:12:48,794 --> 00:12:53,140
As a matter of fact I remember at the beginning of this

294
00:12:53,140 --> 00:12:54,522
in my initial prototype

295
00:12:55,906 --> 00:12:58,188
So let's start with the simple premise, right?

296
00:12:58,188 --> 00:13:00,510
Piloting drones into derelict spaceships, right?

297
00:13:00,510 --> 00:13:03,053
So what I made initially was this simple,

298
00:13:03,053 --> 00:13:05,795
all right, so we're gonna steal more ideas here.

299
00:13:05,795 --> 00:13:08,518
So I made this, I jokingly called it boxes in space.

300
00:13:08,518 --> 00:13:10,259
It was just cubes with a headlamp,

301
00:13:10,259 --> 00:13:13,082
and you were going through this derelict spaceship.

302
00:13:13,082 --> 00:13:15,484
And Randy O'Connor, who did Escape Goat 2

303
00:13:15,484 --> 00:13:17,026
and a whole bunch of other stuff,

304
00:13:17,026 --> 00:13:18,907
he was playing it, and he was like.

305
00:13:19,528 --> 00:13:21,689
And after just a couple minutes, he got done with it.

306
00:13:21,689 --> 00:13:23,350
And he was like, I'm really tense right now.

307
00:13:23,350 --> 00:13:25,671
And his shoulders were up and he was just really tense.

308
00:13:25,671 --> 00:13:28,933
And I was like, wow, that's really impactful for a game

309
00:13:28,933 --> 00:13:30,774
with so little effort into it, right?

310
00:13:30,774 --> 00:13:32,415
So I started exploring a lot of things.

311
00:13:32,415 --> 00:13:34,916
I started exploring the combat and all that stuff.

312
00:13:34,916 --> 00:13:36,717
And those things would kind of work,

313
00:13:36,717 --> 00:13:37,838
but they didn't have that effect

314
00:13:37,838 --> 00:13:41,139
that that simple initial prototype had.

315
00:13:41,139 --> 00:13:41,980
And I actually remember...

316
00:13:43,300 --> 00:13:48,664
Remember struggling with the the combat system actually and Alex Austin. He's right there

317
00:13:48,664 --> 00:13:54,129
Who did gish and he's doing sub-roaster right now. I was like man. I'm really struggling with the combat

318
00:13:54,129 --> 00:13:57,311
Like I don't know what to do, and he was like why don't you not focus on combat?

319
00:13:57,311 --> 00:13:57,931
And I'm like what a dick like

320
00:14:02,122 --> 00:14:04,503
That's such a jerk answer, but it was so right.

321
00:14:04,503 --> 00:14:05,783
And I didn't focus on combat,

322
00:14:05,783 --> 00:14:07,504
and actually the game doesn't focus on combat at all,

323
00:14:07,504 --> 00:14:10,425
and that's probably one of the best things about the game.

324
00:14:10,425 --> 00:14:12,286
So, steal ideas, people.

325
00:14:12,286 --> 00:14:14,787
So, now that the, so the combat wasn't working,

326
00:14:14,787 --> 00:14:17,328
but the drones were, so let's focus on those drones, right?

327
00:14:17,328 --> 00:14:18,768
And moving them around in space.

328
00:14:18,768 --> 00:14:21,770
That's when I got the idea, or actually,

329
00:14:21,770 --> 00:14:24,071
I was suggested the idea, and no one will take credit for it.

330
00:14:24,071 --> 00:14:26,031
No one will admit that they did this.

331
00:14:26,031 --> 00:14:28,432
But they were like, what about a command line interface?

332
00:14:28,432 --> 00:14:30,193
And I was like, that's a horrible idea.

333
00:14:30,193 --> 00:14:30,593
And then I was like,

334
00:14:31,805 --> 00:14:34,025
This is probably my last game, I'm an indie game developer,

335
00:14:34,025 --> 00:14:35,406
why don't I do that?

336
00:14:35,406 --> 00:14:37,066
So I threw in the command line interface,

337
00:14:37,066 --> 00:14:39,067
and then the player fantasy started to become

338
00:14:39,067 --> 00:14:42,508
about being a drone operator and commanding these drones.

339
00:14:42,508 --> 00:14:44,329
And it was really starting to feel really good.

340
00:14:44,329 --> 00:14:49,690
And this is when Pete Angstadt, who did Cannon Brawl,

341
00:14:49,690 --> 00:14:52,951
and he's doing, is it Kingdoms and Castles?

342
00:14:53,603 --> 00:14:56,106
Yeah, and he worked on Abzu.

343
00:14:56,106 --> 00:14:57,428
So when you're getting design help,

344
00:14:57,428 --> 00:14:59,391
it's not always that you want, yes man,

345
00:14:59,391 --> 00:15:01,434
it's not always people that are affirming your ideas.

346
00:15:01,434 --> 00:15:02,535
A lot of times it's really good

347
00:15:02,535 --> 00:15:04,278
if they think your ideas are shit,

348
00:15:04,278 --> 00:15:06,941
because you have to then justify what you're doing

349
00:15:06,941 --> 00:15:08,323
or change what you're doing.

350
00:15:08,623 --> 00:15:10,724
So he completely crapped all over all of this.

351
00:15:10,724 --> 00:15:12,444
He said drones are a horrible idea

352
00:15:12,444 --> 00:15:14,125
because people don't care about drones.

353
00:15:14,125 --> 00:15:16,605
If a drone dies, it's just a piece of metal, right?

354
00:15:16,605 --> 00:15:18,966
If it's a scientist or a space marine or whatever

355
00:15:18,966 --> 00:15:20,506
that's a human and they die, people care.

356
00:15:20,506 --> 00:15:22,066
So that's a bad decision.

357
00:15:22,066 --> 00:15:24,607
Command line interface, hey man, real time strategy games.

358
00:15:24,607 --> 00:15:26,627
Drag select, right click, that's a convention.

359
00:15:26,627 --> 00:15:27,427
Why is it?

360
00:15:27,427 --> 00:15:28,628
It's because over like decades,

361
00:15:28,628 --> 00:15:30,688
people have figured that this stuff works, right?

362
00:15:30,688 --> 00:15:33,028
So hey, let's make people type this clunky interface.

363
00:15:33,028 --> 00:15:34,089
That's really obnoxious.

364
00:15:34,089 --> 00:15:35,129
That's a horrible idea too.

365
00:15:37,669 --> 00:15:38,570
a drone operator.

366
00:15:38,570 --> 00:15:41,031
He was like, nobody wants to be Tank,

367
00:15:41,031 --> 00:15:42,252
everyone wants to be Neo.

368
00:15:42,252 --> 00:15:44,253
This is a Matrix reference.

369
00:15:44,253 --> 00:15:46,275
Everybody wants to fly through the air

370
00:15:46,275 --> 00:15:47,735
and kick people in the head

371
00:15:47,735 --> 00:15:48,856
and shoot them with machine guns.

372
00:15:48,856 --> 00:15:51,378
No one wants to be that guy behind all the computers,

373
00:15:51,378 --> 00:15:52,819
the operator, right, that you call.

374
00:15:55,258 --> 00:15:57,780
And I realized I wanted to be Tank at that point.

375
00:15:57,780 --> 00:16:01,443
But I was like, so how do I justify all this stuff, right?

376
00:16:01,443 --> 00:16:02,844
Like, this was solid.

377
00:16:02,844 --> 00:16:03,965
This wasn't him being a jerk.

378
00:16:03,965 --> 00:16:05,286
This was really good feedback.

379
00:16:05,286 --> 00:16:07,068
And these were really good arguments.

380
00:16:07,068 --> 00:16:08,809
And I had to come up with a justification

381
00:16:08,809 --> 00:16:10,170
or I had to change these things.

382
00:16:10,170 --> 00:16:12,132
I couldn't just be like, oh, I'm just kicking over

383
00:16:12,132 --> 00:16:14,254
design principles left and right because I'm an indie.

384
00:16:14,254 --> 00:16:14,514
It's like.

385
00:16:15,255 --> 00:16:16,256
you have to actually justify this stuff.

386
00:16:16,256 --> 00:16:18,337
And I was like, why am I doing this?

387
00:16:18,337 --> 00:16:19,799
Why am I doing all this stuff?

388
00:16:19,799 --> 00:16:21,520
And it goes back to Randy feeling tense,

389
00:16:21,520 --> 00:16:24,183
which was the strongest thing I'd had in the game so far.

390
00:16:24,183 --> 00:16:26,825
And I was like, this stuff feels tense.

391
00:16:26,825 --> 00:16:28,887
Why does this stuff feel tense?

392
00:16:28,887 --> 00:16:31,529
This stuff feels tense because this stuff feels real.

393
00:16:32,850 --> 00:16:36,752
If I hit up on a keyboard and a human moves up,

394
00:16:36,752 --> 00:16:39,473
that doesn't happen in the real world.

395
00:16:39,473 --> 00:16:41,635
That can happen with a drone.

396
00:16:41,635 --> 00:16:44,176
Using command line interfaces to control robots

397
00:16:44,176 --> 00:16:46,637
feels visceral and it feels real.

398
00:16:46,637 --> 00:16:48,718
Being a drone operator to me feels more realistic

399
00:16:48,718 --> 00:16:50,719
than flying through the air and kicking people in the head.

400
00:16:52,740 --> 00:16:56,243
So, all of a sudden, it's all started coming together,

401
00:16:56,243 --> 00:16:57,465
and I was like, that's what it is,

402
00:16:57,465 --> 00:16:59,286
is that this game feels real.

403
00:16:59,286 --> 00:17:01,868
So that became a pillar for me.

404
00:17:01,868 --> 00:17:04,691
And again, that's sort of like a feeling or an emotion,

405
00:17:04,691 --> 00:17:07,694
right, is this realism, that I'm really the drone operator.

406
00:17:07,694 --> 00:17:09,795
So now the question is, all right,

407
00:17:09,795 --> 00:17:11,097
we've come this far with realism,

408
00:17:11,097 --> 00:17:14,460
now I'm talking about how these things can be pervasive,

409
00:17:14,460 --> 00:17:15,621
where do we go from there?

410
00:17:15,621 --> 00:17:16,862
How do we take realism and apply it

411
00:17:16,862 --> 00:17:17,682
to the rest of the game, okay?

412
00:17:17,682 --> 00:17:18,383
No music.

413
00:17:21,939 --> 00:17:26,865
I come from a film background, and if you take a soundtrack out of a film, the film sucks.

414
00:17:26,865 --> 00:17:32,191
It's like chopping off your legs. I don't know if you've ever watched a scene from a movie and then watched it without the soundtrack.

415
00:17:32,191 --> 00:17:38,398
It's amazing how much you lose from that. So this isn't like, oh, I think I'll do this. This is like a strong decision.

416
00:17:39,059 --> 00:17:40,921
But that was my pillar, it was realism.

417
00:17:40,921 --> 00:17:42,342
And music is non-diegetic.

418
00:17:42,342 --> 00:17:44,604
And what I mean by that is I don't walk around

419
00:17:44,604 --> 00:17:46,426
and hear a score playing in my head every time.

420
00:17:46,426 --> 00:17:48,608
It would be awesome if when I walked into a room

421
00:17:48,608 --> 00:17:50,610
something like that happened, but it doesn't.

422
00:17:50,610 --> 00:17:54,313
And so it's non-diegetic, and it doesn't fit in my game.

423
00:17:54,313 --> 00:17:56,035
And that was a really scary decision,

424
00:17:56,035 --> 00:17:57,617
but I was like, hey, if I'm gonna do it,

425
00:17:57,617 --> 00:17:58,758
I'm gonna go all the way.

426
00:17:58,758 --> 00:17:59,979
I already put a command line interface

427
00:17:59,979 --> 00:18:00,820
in the game, for Christ's sakes.

428
00:18:01,280 --> 00:18:04,343
So that became a decision.

429
00:18:04,343 --> 00:18:07,126
Another thing is that at the beginning of the game,

430
00:18:07,126 --> 00:18:09,629
people, I started realizing I have to go further with this

431
00:18:09,629 --> 00:18:12,171
because people were like, oh, I'm the drone,

432
00:18:12,171 --> 00:18:15,195
or okay, now I'm playing as the drone operator.

433
00:18:15,195 --> 00:18:17,037
And to steal another idea, David Rosen,

434
00:18:17,037 --> 00:18:18,158
who does overgrowth, was like,

435
00:18:18,158 --> 00:18:20,901
why don't you have the player walk up to a bed of monitors

436
00:18:20,901 --> 00:18:22,743
and sit down and then you zoom in on a monitor.

437
00:18:22,743 --> 00:18:23,804
Now they know they're the drone operator.

438
00:18:24,284 --> 00:18:25,364
And I liked that at first.

439
00:18:25,364 --> 00:18:26,585
And then I was like, no, that doesn't work at all

440
00:18:26,585 --> 00:18:28,346
because then I'm not the drone operator.

441
00:18:28,346 --> 00:18:31,067
I'm playing the drone operator who's already in the game

442
00:18:31,067 --> 00:18:32,787
because I'm not moving my head.

443
00:18:32,787 --> 00:18:34,528
I'm not in that room.

444
00:18:34,528 --> 00:18:36,629
I wanted your monitor to be your monitor.

445
00:18:36,629 --> 00:18:38,629
I wanted your keyboard to be your keyboard

446
00:18:38,629 --> 00:18:39,930
because that's real to me.

447
00:18:39,930 --> 00:18:41,851
So what I did was when the game begins,

448
00:18:41,851 --> 00:18:43,471
we'd show a boot screen

449
00:18:43,471 --> 00:18:45,552
because we're letting you know this computer

450
00:18:45,552 --> 00:18:46,973
you're sitting in front of is your computer.

451
00:18:47,613 --> 00:18:48,973
This is you.

452
00:18:48,973 --> 00:18:50,254
You're not playing the drone operator,

453
00:18:50,254 --> 00:18:51,614
you are the drone operator.

454
00:18:51,614 --> 00:18:53,815
And so you can see how this is just this notion

455
00:18:53,815 --> 00:18:55,295
of realism is just starting to pervade

456
00:18:55,295 --> 00:18:58,496
every molecule of this game, right?

457
00:18:58,496 --> 00:19:01,857
Same thing, we originally had this closed circuit TV look.

458
00:19:01,857 --> 00:19:04,778
And actually, and so slam imagery is a lot closer

459
00:19:04,778 --> 00:19:06,698
to what you actually get when you're talking about robots

460
00:19:06,698 --> 00:19:07,979
and how they see the world, you know,

461
00:19:07,979 --> 00:19:09,619
casting out dots and doing edge detection

462
00:19:09,619 --> 00:19:10,679
and stuff like that.

463
00:19:10,679 --> 00:19:13,480
And I remember tweeting out, like, the comparison picture.

464
00:19:13,820 --> 00:19:15,001
and being like, what do you guys like?

465
00:19:15,001 --> 00:19:17,402
And most people like the CCTV better.

466
00:19:17,402 --> 00:19:20,623
At that point, I mean, we changed things a bit from here.

